column168: NATX 37752 was noted by carrier personnel with product on sides of car.  Car isolated and shipper notified.    Shipper representatives, Hepaco, Inc, responded and found the threaded liquid valve loose.  Attempts to tighten the valve were unsucessful because the liquid valve stem was obstructed by the magnetic gauging device when the valve was turned.  The entire valve housing was removed by loosening and removing the valve flange bolts.  The liquid valve was removed from the valve base, new tape sealant applied to the threads and gasket sealer applied to the base gasket.  The valve assembly was then reassembled, reapplied and the flange bolts properly tightened stopping the release.    Note: The protective housing had an intact shipper's seal.  The seal was removed and the housing cover opened to expose the leaking valve.  The leaking valve had a tag applied which read " Defective Valve Leaking".  It is unknown by whom or when this tag was applied but it had to be in place before the housing cover was closed and sealed.    See photo attached.

column168: Product odor was reported emanating from PLCX 129127 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) in the railyard. A BNSF hazardous material responder inspected PLCX 129127 finding no liquid leaks, but a product vapor hiss emanating from between the manway nozzle and the manway lid. All manway securement bolts were tool tight. Inspection of the manway gasket revealed that it was partially hanging over the manway lip, ripped in several places and generally deteriorated due to age. The responder had no suitable replacement gasket on hand and the manway was resecured. PLCX 129127 was isolated in the railyard and the shipper was notified to provide a replacement gasket. After the replacement gasket was installed and the manway was secured by1930 hrs. MDT, 9/03/07, no further product vapor release or product odor was detectable. PLCX 129127 was released to proceed to its destination.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: A BNSF switchman reported PROX 42167 (DOT 111A100W6 tank car) leaking product from the manway area when it was switched into a departure track in the railyard. A BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder immediately inspected PROX 42167 and reported finding 6 of 8 manway securement bolts only hand tight. The responder properly tool tightened the loose securement bolts by 1100 hrs. CDT, 9/04/07. All spillage was water diluted. PROX 42167 departed the railyard without further incident.

column169: 9/8/07; At approximately 9:15AM, conductor of CR train CA-11 reported a leak from tank car UTLX 201016, load Waste Flammable Liquid, Toxic, NOS, while at M.P. 17 on the Pennsgrove Secondary.      Further inspection by Conrail Risk Manager A. Richter, and emergency response contractor REACT Environmental Services, found a piece of gasket sticking out from under the 8-bolt manway cover (underneath the manway cover handle area) and 5 of 8 manway cover securement bolts less than hand tight.  Opening of the manway cover during inspection revealed the piece of butyl rubber gasket observed prior to opening the cover was one end of a full butyl rubber gasket, with the remainder hanging inside the car with the product.  The applied garlock manway cover gasket was also found to be scored at the manway cover handle area.  Both cut gasket, and the applied gasket were removed, a butyl rubber manway nozzle boot gasket reapplied and manway cover secured tool tight.  Sides of car were wiped down where minimal amount of product had seeped out.  Car/train was okayed for movement to original destination at 12:00 noon.

column168: Intermodal container TCNU 973215 in the intermodal parking lot was reported leaking an unknown substance from the underside of this container. TCNU 973215 was carefully moved to the containment area for further investigation. Shipper contractor inspected the lading inside TCNU 973215 and found two leaking 55 gallon steel drums (UN Package Specification 1A1/Y1.8/300/07/USA/M4601) of resin solution. These drums sat atop a stacked pallet near mid-container. The drums were dented at the sidewalls above the bottom chime; and stress cracks developed at the deepest part of the dent. Product leaked from these cracks. It appeared that the overhang of a plywood separator atop a pallet of drums in front of the two compromised drums came in contact with the damaged drums during transit. Contractor overpacked the two damaged drums and cleaned all spillage. The overpacked drums were returned to the rear of TCNU 973215 after all lading was replaced and properly adjusted for continued transportation.

The liquid Oxygen shipment loaded in an IMO 7 cargo tank number IECU100022-6 was lifted to the Horizon Hunter cargo vessel at the port of Oakland California for discharge at the Port of Guam.  The Horizon Hunter had left Oakland and had completed cargo operations in Hawaii and was in route to Guam when the vessel personnel noticed the oxygen tank venting at 0730 in the morning on September 9th, 2006.  The venting continued all day.  The Captain phoned the National Response Center and reported the incident to me.  It is believed that the initial venting of the vapor caused the valve to freeze and it did not reseat properly.  The shipper was advised of the incident as well.  The valve reseated and the venting ceased prior to the vessel arrival at the port of Guam.
column169: Bulk cargo tanks are designed to vent to relieve pressure.  This very cold product venting in a very high temperature and high humidity area could have contributed to the freezing vent problem.  I do not have a solution to avoidint this type of problem.

The release was reported at 1756 hours EST on Monday, September 17,2007 by Mr. Michael Baldwin, Safety Manager for Flying JTransportation, LLC and Mr.  Tom Moritz, Selective Risk Manager, HMHTTC Response,Inc. to Mr. Walter  Hingle of the Louisiana State Police Transportation & Environmental Safety  Section - Hazardous Materials Hotline. The notification was made due to an  overturned MC-307 tank truck carrying diesel fuel located at 17901 Hwy 71N, Mira LA.    The release was reported at approximately 1310 hours (No Police Report yet has  been issued) and lasted until 2030 hours when the fuel tanker was transferred.  The tractor number was 1208 & the trailer number P227. The Caddo Parrish  Sheriff, Hazmat, and Fire units responded for this overturned tanker. Once  emergency crews arrived, the product leaking from the dome lids was contained  into poly buckets.    The circumstances leading to the accident are still under investigation by the  Caddo Parrish Sheriff's Office and the Safety Department for Flying J  Transportation. The driver was transporting 7,950 gallons diesel fuel (CAS #  88334-30-5) UN1993, DOT Class 3, PG III,(MSDS Enclosed)  from 4731 Viking Driver, Bossier City, LA 71111 to Highway 108 Texarkana AR  71854. The PRO # was 1888979. It is estimated approximately 20 gallons of  diesel fuel was released through the dome lids at the on set of the incident. The  Caddo Hazmat Unit attempted to seal the leak with the use of a Plug and Dike  material around the leaking domes with no success. The response team then  placed containment units under each of the three leaking dome lids.  Additionally, a total of 5 gallons of oil and approximately 20 gallons of diesel  fuel were lost from the tractor as a result of the accident.    Highway 71 was closed, according to Sgt. Mike Grey of the Caddo Parrish Sheriff  & Hazmat Response Unit, from 1310 to 2157 hours. The response team from  Highway 59 out of Texarkana, AR responded to the site to transfer the product  and remediate the soil.    The response crew developed a safety plan to transfer the product from the  damaged tanker to an awaiting tanker. The crew donned Nomex fire-gear  and/or Nomex coveralls and initially, grounded and bonded the tankers. The  response team then began drilling the tanker into each of the three compartments  at 1700 hours and completed the drilling at 1800 hours. The response team  began vacuuming product shortly thereafter and transferred to an awaiting  Flying J tanker (Truck no. 1092 & Trailer no. P472). The transfer was completed  at 2030 hours. The crew then stood-by until the wrecker company; Lloyd's  Wrecker Service up-righted and removed the damaged T/T. The response team  then secured the site with absorbent boom at either end of the spill to ensure containment until they returned the following day to excavate the contaminated soil. column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Valve Open
column168: A BNSF train crew reported entrained tank car TILX 194067 leaking product from the top fitting area at a BNSF crew change station (Stratton, NE). A BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder inspected entrained TILX 194067. Valve housing seal numbered 0702730 was removed. Responder reported finding the liquid valve partially open (3/8 inch from closed-stop) and its closure plug five full turns loose. The responder closed the valve and tool tightened the closure plug, ending any further product release. All spillage evaporated and no ground impact was evident.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column62: Deterioration or Aging; Defective Component or Device
column168: A BNSF railcar inspection in the railyard of an outbound train in the process of being made up, revealed UTLX 30102 with a fresh commodity stain on its side shell which appeared to emanate from the manway area. A BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder immediately inspected UTLX 30102. The responder reported that the manway bolts were extremely tool tight. The 18 inch manway gasket was found to be deteriorated, compressed and torn. Approximately 1/3 of the circumference of this torn gasket was hanging down inside the manway nozzle. A new gasket was applied and the manway cover was resecured. Seal numbered BNSF 06157849 was applied. The prior seal removed was illegible. All spillage evaporated on the shell and no ground impact was evident.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: The terminal was notified that during a railcar switch by CSX railroad, railcar OLNX-32027 emitted a vapor cloud from the rupture disc area.  The railcar contained hydrochloric acid.    A vendor, Hepaco, was called to inspect the railcar and discovered the rupture disc housing bolts were loose and tightened the bolts, however, once the railcar was moved, another vapor cloud emitted from the rupture disc area.      The shipper was contacted and the product was removed and the railcar was taken out of service for further investigation and repair.
column169: Recommendations include continued diligence on the part of the railraod to observe, identify and report unordinary vapor releases; notification of railcar manufacturers of failed systems, preventitive maintenance and improved and continued diligence of railcar arrival and departure inspection of various components.    SUPPLEMENTAL REPORT    RECOMMENDATIONS INCLUDE: 1) CLOSE OBSERVATION ON THE PART OF THE RAILROAD TO IDENTIFY AND REPORT RELEASES WHEN THEY OCUR. 2) PROVIDE AND RECEIVE INFORMATION TO/FROM RAILCAR MANUFACTURERS REGARDING FAILED COMPONENTS AND RAILCAR SYSTEMS. 3) CONTINUE TO IMPROVE PROCESSES IN PLACE FOR INSPECTING RAILCARS DURING ARRIVAL AND DEPARTURE PHASES OF TRANSPORTATION.

column168: On 09/18/2007 at 0245hrs a switch job from CSX railroad was switching the Philadelphia Transflo terminal operated by Kinder Morgan Material Services.  While moving railcar TILX 100488 containing sulfuric the switch crew reported a "puff" of white smoke and some liquid product sloshing and running down the sides of the tank.  The car was switched back into the terminal on track T03.      Railcar TILX 100488 was inspected by Kinder Morgan Material Services.  Upon opening the tool tight dome lid it was discovered that the manway gasket was ripped and stretched and completly severed on one side.    The gasket was replaced.
column169: It is recommended that the railroad and terminal operators maintain a level of diligence observing, identifying and reporting unordinary releases, preventative maintenance and railcar arrival and departure inspections.

CN transportation employee had liquid spilled on him from top of tank car GATX 43765 during switching operations at the Verso Paper Plant, Quinnesec, MI. All appropriate department notified and tank car isolated. CN Dangerous Goods Team members responded noting loose manway bolts. Gasket replaced, manway properly secured, car decontaminated and released for movement.    While the UPRR shows as the shipper of record, this car started its trip from DOW, Plaquemine, LA and was delivered to the Dial Corporation, Montgomery, IL. Dial Corp. was unable to unload car from bottom outlet so turned car back to DOW. Car then moved in error on the UPRR and BNSF until re-routed from Beaumont, TX to Verso Paper, Quinnesec, MI. Car was unloaded from the top by Verso Paper and is now in route back to DOW at Plaquemine, LA.

column168: CSX Transporation Hazardous Materials was notified that UTLX 641827 had a slosh leak from the top of the car while in motion. CSX Transportation dispatched SPSI to respond to the Cumberland Rail Yard to investigate. SPSI arrived to find that the manway cover bolts were not tool tight but were hand tight. There was some corrosion on the manway nozzle which also contributed to the manway cover gasket not completely seating against the manway nozzle. The car also did not have the required outage. SPSI pumped off approximately 1000 gallons of product into a tank truck. The car was then prepared for transportation and released.  UTLX 641827 had to be moved from the classification yard to a spur track in the yard.    Cause Code:  200  NARRI:  5(5+5+0) x (2+0) = 100

column168: On 09/06/07 at 08:32 hrs., CSXT Train Master David Rose, reported that tank car UTLX 13882, load Sulfuric Acid, had a slosh leak from the top of the rail car when moved. The car was isolated and the shipper was notified. The shipper, Zinifex Taylor, contacted emergency response contractor, RESCAR, to respond and repair the leak. Once on site, RESCAR reported that 3 of the manway bolts were less than tool tight and the seal was broken. The three bolts were tightened and a new seal was applied. The car was secured and released to final destination.          NARRI :  5 (5+5+0) * (2+0) = 100  Cause Code = 200

column168: On 09/08/07 at 02:05 hrs., CSXT Train Master Bobby Duhon, at the CSXT Birmingham, AL., yard, reported that tank car ACFX 83850, load Crude Sulfate Turpentine, was sloshing liquid from the top of the car when moved. No product was hitting the ground at this time. Local authorities were notified and the car was isolated at a safe location within yard limits. A CSXT emergency response contractor, HEPACO Environmental, was contacted to respond to the scene.  Upon arrival, HEPACO advised that 5 of the 8 manway bolts were less than tool tight and the manway gasket was defective. A new manway gasket was installed and the 8 bolts were tool tightened. The car was secured and released to destination.          NARRI :  5 (5+1+0) * (2+0) = 60  Cause Code = 200

column168: On 09/14/07 at 15:39 hrs., it was reported that tank car WCHX23123, load Crude Sulfate Turpentine, was discovered to have an odor coming from the car at CSXT's Queensgate yard in Cincinnati, Ohio.  It was determined by CSXT field personnel, that vapors were escaping from around the manway cover. It also appeared some of the manway gasket was protruding from under the manway cover and base.  A CSXT emergency response contractor, Veolia Environmental, was dispatched to the scene to inspect the car and make repairs.  Upon arrival, Veolia found the tank car had a bad manway cover gasket and proceeded to install a temporary Teflon rope gasket, since a replacement gasket was not immediately available. The manway cover was then secured from further release and the odor stopped.  It was recommended that once the car was unloaded, that a new manway cover gasket be installed.    Cause Code:  209  NARRI: 5 (3+1+0) X (2+0) = 40

column168: On 09/17/07 at 0803 hrs., CSXT Trainmaster, Jason Bishop of the Louisville KY., terminal reported that tank car ACFX 88868, load Ethanol, was discovered leaking from the bottom of car. The drip from the bottom outlet valve was reported to be 1 drop every 5 seconds. The car was moved to a lead track near the tower where Summit Environmental could inspect the car and fix the valve. Inspection by Summit found the bottom outlet handle to be in the closed and locked position. The seal was cut; the handle was opened and closed several times causing the leak to slow down. Summit returned the next day opened and closed the valve several more time and the leak stopped. The cap was tightened with a wrench and the car was sent to destination.             NARRI :  5 (5+3+0) * (2+0) = 80  Cause Code = 564

Cargo came in on NW914/31Aug our codeshare partner. When our ground handler went to pick up the cargo,hedetected a strange odor. In total there were 4 aircraft pallets being picked up from NW. He checked around thepallets, but did not find or visually see anything unusual. The condition on the ramp side of NW airlines were dark(around 2345hrs) and since there were many aircraft equipment and the aircraft next to our cargo, he assumedtheodor was not coming from our cargo. He signed off the cargo about 2355hrs and proceeded to transport the 4 units toour warehouse, which is aboutIO minutes away using the airport service road. Upon breakdown, apparent forkliftdamage was found. One of the dangerous goods was found leaking and two other of the same shipment appeared tobe damaged. The warehouse ground handlers notified JAL management at which time all personnel were toevacuated from the warehouse. JAL management notified LAFD, APO POLICE, Airport Authorities and left phonemessage with FAA.Warehouse main doors were left open to keep fumes from collecting in one area. LAFD HAZMATdepartment afterinvestigation and checking documentation gave okay to resume operation, but to keep infected areacleared untilproper HAZMAT clean-up/disposal was hired to clean up and dispose of damaged hazardous material.
column169: Additional training will be given to our warehouse handlers on the acceptance of hazardous materials and what signsto check for. Also, refresher/reminder training will be given on handling of hazardous material (safety) andemergency response. We forwarded all the information to our NW Airlines, our code share partner for investigationpurpose regarding this incident. — Will forward hard copies via mail of: a. This reportb. airway bill copy c. dangerous goods declarationd. our emergency medical report regarding one of our staff- possibleexposure to fumes. Immediate release after evaluation. e. documentation-Uniform Hazardous Waste Manifest Disposal ** Will forward FD Report nbr/Police Report nbr when received.**

They contracted Chemical Detection Services to conduct the cleanup.  A 55 gallon drum of Osmose K-33(60%) Wood Preservative was found leaking. It had a small crack 1/2 inch in size. This drum was apart from the other four drums containing the same product which were located in the fronr of the container.

column168: On Wednesday, 9-19-07 at approximately 12:45PM, our hazmat driver reported to us that one of his 275 gallon IBC's of 45% Potassium Hydroxide, solution leaked en-route to a nearby customer.  Approximately 20 gallons of material leaked into the box of the truck and onto the trucks rear tires.  A pedestrian on a bicycle received a spray of material as the truck drove by.  He was taken to the hospital for treatment and released.  The IBC's discharge valve somehow partially opened after the driver reported going oversome potholes.  The driver immediately closed the valve and placed containment under his truck to soak up the spill.  The Buffalo Fire Dept. and the Buffalo Police closed the road while our spill response team cleaned up the spill materials.
column169: The IBC's had been loaded sideways in the bed of the truck to minimize movement between them.  It is possible that when the truck hit the potholes, the IBC bounced, hit the outside wall of the truck and opened the valve. Our loading procedures have been changed and our personnel have been re-trained to only load IBCs onto the truck with the discharge valves facing the rear of the truck. Additional load straps will be used to prevent container movement. This will prevent the valves from striking the outside walls of the truck in the event of the truck hitting raod hazards.

column168: At approximately 16:20 on September 20, 2007 a van trailer stored at Clean Harbors Environmental Services in-transit storage yard located in Baltimore, MD experienced a minor release of hazardous waste material from a non-bulk package.  The driver of the vehicle noticed small amount of liquid on the floor of the van trailer while performing a post-trip vehicle inspection.  Additionally, the driver notices a small amount of liquid starting to seep through the floor boards of the trailer.   He immediately notified his supervisor of the spill and an in house emergency response crew was dispatched to identify the source of release and to take all necessary corrective actions.  Upon review of the paperwork, the emergency response crew donned appropriate protective equipment and entered the trailer.  An inspection of the non-bulk packages in the trailer identified that a single 55-gallon UN 1A1 container of Class 8 liquid developed a small pin-hole on the bottom and released about 1 gallon of material onto the trailer floor.  The response crew immediately used a chemically compatible absorbent material to prevent any additional liquid seeping through the trailer onto the pavement below.   After the absorbent materials were applied to the floor of the trailer, the trailer was moved into a secondary containment bay in order to avoid any additional contamination of the parking area. The leaking drum was placed in a suitable salvage drum and all of the absorbent was collected and placed into appropriate container for disposal at an approved hazardous waste management facility.  Please note that approximately one quart of material leaked through the floorboards of the van-trailer onto the pavement the majority of the released material was contained in the van trailer.     The time frame from the initial notice of the spill until the drum was overpacked and the spill clean up was approximately 1 hours.  All of the released material was collected and no offsite impact occurred.
column169: Our investigation determined that the cause of the incident was deterioration of the container on storage and insufficient inspection prior to transportation.    The individuals responsible for preparing this shipment for transportation will be informed of this incident and a request will be made to the involved parties to undergo additional training on container inspections.   Additionally, the shipper will be asked to review the compatibility of the lading with the container used prior to any additional shipments.

Subjuct vehicle ( Tractor, Semi-trailer, Pup ) traveling in left lane of interstate highway. A recap tire lost it's cap. As the rubber from cap rotated, still attached to casing, the rubber beat the safety chain, that stops the valve from viberating open, from the fender. the chain came loose and allowed the valve to viborate open. The liquid of the load came out the valve preasured the valve cover (camlock) and the preasure forced the ears of the camlock cover to open and allowed the liquid to splashed on the highway. The spray lasted for approximately one mile before the driver could take an exit and drive off the paved portion of the road to a dirt area. Nothing failed except the tire. The Wyoming DOT has covered the spill with tar to eliminate the "Yellow" marking. The lost cargo is no longer a hazmat after it cools.
column169: This was probably a one time situation as we have been hauling Molten Sulfur 24/7 for 17 years and this has never happened before. We are in the process of trying a new procedure that will hold the ears of the camlock up and not allow preasure to force the cap off.

column168: On September 15, 2007, at approximately 0200 hours, a railway tankcar UTLX 13345, loaded with Phosphoric acid, liquid, UN1805 PG III, was reported leaking at the Kansas City Southern Railway (KCSR) Jackson, Mississippi yard. The tank car was discovered leaking from a ruptured disc. The shipper representative responded to the site and replaced the disc and washed down the car.  There were no injuries, no damage to the environment.                                                                                                                CODE: 441  NARRI: 5(5+3+0)x(2+0)=80    *Rupture disc
column169: On The Kansas City Southern Railway (KCSR), shippers are immediately notified of all HAZMAT releases.  For non-accident releases (a.k.a. package or closure defects), where possible, shippers (responsible party) are requested to respond, repair and remediate.  By immediately involving the shipper, in-depth knowledge of the release cause is gained by the same organization that can implement process changes to prevent recurrence.  After each NAR incident, KCSR provides outreach to the shipper to help investigate root-cause factors for correction.  For non-accident related releases, the shipper should be contacted directly for details associated with actions taken to prevent recurrence.

column168: Driver did not back all the way up to the unloading station and unloading pipe came out of the unloading station while unloading. Product spilled into the containment area.

column168: Veolia field personnel performed their routine hazardous waste management services to a client in Bloomington, CA, which included the lab pack of chemicals and the shipment of various waste streams.  Eight - one gallon containers of cumyl hydroperoxide, <=90%, were packaged into two 14-gallon UN rated fiber containers (4x1 gallon in each container) with the appropriate absorbent and sealed properly.  All lab pack containers and waste stream containers were properly loaded, segregated, placarded and secured on a Veolia truck for transportation from the customer site to a Veolia TSDF located in Azusa, CA.  Shortly after the Veolia driver left the site, at approximately 4:15 p.m., he noticed during his regular mirror checks that smoke was emanating from the back of his trailer.  At this point he was traveling westbound on the 210 freeway in the city of Rancho Cucamonga, and felt that there was not enough room on the side of the expressway to safely pull over, so he exited at the first available cross street.  The Veolia truck exited at Milliken Street and proceeded northbound approximately 40 feet to the first available safe pull off area.  The Veolia driver then unlocked the back door of his trailer and opened it.  More smoke bellowed out of the back of the truck, so he closed it immediately.  The driver then called the Veolia Branch Field Services Operations Manager, and informed him of the situation.  The driver was instructed by the Operations Manager to call 911 immediately.       The Veolia driver donned the appropriate PPE and entered the back of the trailer and determined that one of the 14-gallon drums containing the cumyl hydroperoxide was smoldering and generating a large amount of smoke.  He was able to determine that there were no visible flames, just heavy amounts of smoke.  The lid of the container was taken out to verify the hazard class and shipping label to provide emergency responders with proper information to handle the situation.  The Rancho Cucamonga Fire Department showed up on-site at approximately 5:00 p.m. and assessed the situation.  They called for their Hazmat team who came and extinguished the drum with water and removed it from the truck.  After the smoldering was extinguished, the Hazmat team packaged the contents of the burned fiber drum into a 5-gallon poly pail.  This 5-gallon pail was then over-packed into a 14-gal poly container.  Veolia Hazmat responders arrived onsite at approximately 5:30 p.m. and cleaned the back of the truck and picked up any residual absorbent from the street.  They also inspected the packaging by the fire department and found that there was still heat being generated inside the overpack drum.  In response, the inner container was removed from the 14-gallon drum and inspected, revealing a soiled rag wrapped around one of the gallon containers of cumyl hydroperoxide.  Veolia responders believe this to be the root cause of the incident, as this dirty rag probably contained some organics and
column169: In response, Veolia has discussed the incident in subsequent weekly safety meetings, focusing on the details/events of the incident, root causes, newly instituted protocol changes for handling organic peroxides/oxidizers, preventative measures, etc.  Veolia has revised, in a formal document, a new SOP for the safe handling/packaging (in lab-packs)/shipping of organic peroxides and oxidizers.  This SOP has been promptly distributed to all field personnel, project managers, field supervisors and all other individuals that might be involved in hazardous waste shipments.  This new SOP has been implemented immediately and along with complying with all DOT packaging requirements, specifically states that all organic peroxides (OP) and oxidizers are to be sealed individually in plastic bags with no other materials present in the container.  All drums are to be lined with an additional poly liner (double-lined) and all caps of bottles containing OP and oxidizers shall be sealed and secured to help prevent leakage.  All OP and oxidizers will be packed with clay absorbent unless there is a compatibility concern/issue.  Strict segregation requirements will continue to be followed in packaging and loading of these materials.

column168: We were in the process of unloading an above ground heating oil tank (for replacment)when the flange on the discharge side of the pump came off because it was not properly secured by the technician. The product flowed onto the driveway at the residence and into a storm drain on customers property into a local stream. The Maryland Department of Environment was notified and responded to site and provided assistance in clean-up. A water tanker was used to flush the stream and oil product was removed.
column169: Procedural error was reviewed with all technicians doing similar job functions. Mandatory use of locking devices to ensure flanges cannot come open during pump-out operation has been implemented.

column168: AS OUR DRIVER WAS DELIVERING FUEL INTO THE CUSTOMER'S AST, THE HOSE ADAPTER BROKE. THIS ALLOWED APPROXIMATELY 25 GALLONS OF DIESEL FUEL TO BE RELEASED. ALL OF THE DIESEL WAS CONTAINED IN THE DYKE AREA SURROUNDING THE AST AND WAS CLEANED UP BY OUR DRIVER.

THE DRIVER ATTEMPTED TO DELIVER TOO MUCH FUEL INTO THE CUSTOMER'S UST. HE WAS UNABLE TO GET ALL OF THE DIESEL FUEL DRAINED FROM HIS HOSE. WHEN HE DISCONNECTED THE HOSE, APPROXIMATELY 15 GALLONS SPILLED ONTO CONCRETE PAD AND ASPHALT PARKING LOT. THE SPILL WAS IMMEDIATELY CLEANED UP BY THE DRIVER AND ANOTHER ADVANTAGE TANK LINES EMPLOYEE. NO FURTHER ENVIRONMENTAL IMPACT IS EXPECTED.
column169: ADVANTAGE TANK LINES WILL CONTINUE TO TRAIN AND ENFORCE PROPER DELIVERY PROTOCOL.

column168: Darin Jones, Yardmaster, reported a chemical odor emitting from the low side of the bowl in the Livonia Yard in Livonia, LA. TomRobinson, Manager Hazardous Materials Management, was notified and responded.    Upon arrival, tank car ACFX 71267 was found tobe emitting an intermittent odor from within the protective housing. Inspection revealed a slight vapor release from the plug of the air inlet valve. The plug was tightened an additional two turns and this stopped the release. Due to the strong and enduring odor characteristic of the commodity, a bleach solution was applied to the interior of the protective housing and this neutralized the odor.    09:18 PM, Charles Slater, Director of Terminal Operations advised a conductor was exposed to the material released from Tankcar ACFX 71267 in the Livonia Yard. Mr. Slater further advised the employee was experiencing irritation on his face, neck, shoulders, and sinuses. Mr. Slater stated the employee was also experiencing a headache. Mr. Slater further stated John Valley, Manager, took the employee to the Baton Rouge General Hospital.    9/15/07, At 06:11 AM, Robinson stated yard personnel complained the odor remained in the yard at 03:00 AM and the car was isolated onto track #105. Mr. Robinson advised after re-inspection he discovered avapor release from the pressure relief valve and a Technician of U.S. Environmental Company, a contractor, was en route to helpreplace the o-rings. During this operation it was discovered that the valve stem of the pressure relief valve was loose and o-ring replacement did not stop the vapor release. The shipper, Arkema made arrangements for RESCAR technicians to replace the pnrelief valve while United States Environmental personnel drew a vacuum and scrubbed vapors to eliminate any odor release. The pressure relief valve was successfully replaced on Sunday, 9/16/07 and the tank was pressure tested by RESCAR on Tuesday, 9/18/07.    PART III - PACKING INFORMATION: Question 25. (continued):  3. column168: It was discovered during a vehicle inspection that at least one container out of a load of 28 had begun to "weep", or leak its liquid contents onto the floor of the trailer. The liquid then began to "drip" onto the asphalt surface of the temporary storage yard.     An immediate in-house emergency response was initiated and the necessary actions were taken to permit entry into the trailer; identify the leaker(s); and then to mitigate any further release of the material. The in-house emergency response team over-packed the leaking containers, and because the shipment comprised 24 additional containers of the same hazardous material stream, the decision was made to go ahead and over-pack all the individual containers of the entire shipment. This precaution was taken to eliminate the risk that additional leaks might occur while the load was in-transit.     (Note - While the emergency response was on-going, the offeror/generator of the shipment was notified of the problem.)     The leaker(s) were identified as 55 gallon 1A1 closed-head drums containing waste perchloroethylene solution. Upon inspection of the containers it was noted that the release emanated from one or more "pin-holes" in the outer surface.
column169: The offeror/shipper was notified that this transporter will not accept any further hazardous materials from them until the appropriate containers are selected for future use.

column168: According to the information obtained, the following occurred.  Upon inspection of freight at the Alliance Airlines facility located at the JFK International Airport, a leak was discovered.  Upon further inspection, one (1) 10-liter jerrican of environmentally hazardous liquid, nos was discovered damaged.  Approximately 2 gallons of free product were released to the concrete surface at the facility.  Site was secured, a Material Safety Data Sheet was referenced, and H.M.H.T.T.C., Inc. of Linden, New Jersey was dispatched to perform the cleanup.  Upon arrival, H.M.H.T.T.C., Inc. applied oil dry to the free product, which was immediately swept up, and containerized into one (1) 30-gallon recovery drum, along with the damaged container, pending disposal.  Disposal will be coordinated in accordance with local, state, and federal regulations.  There were no injuries or exposures reported.
column169: Since the release was accidental, and appears to be related to improper handling prior to arriving at the Alliance Airlines facility, no plans currently exist to prevent recurrence.  Alliance Airlines will continue to reinforce safe handling procedures and guidelines to all personnel.

column168: A BNSF mechanical carman reported an inbound train arriving in the railyard had an entrained NAHX 54372 (an AAR C113 three compartment covered hopper) that was spilling product from the A-end bottom hopper outlet. The carman was able to close this outlet and secure it with wire cabling. The A-end bottom outlet door was open approximately two inches and its locking assembly was missing with seal intact. A BNSF environmental contractor used a vacuum truck to vacuum up all spillage that was found. A nearby agricultural entity was able to use the recovered ammonium nitrate from the vacuum truck for agricultural purposes. The shipper was notified to send NAHX 54372 to a qualified repair facility for repairs to the A-end hopper outlet's locking mechanism after it was unloaded; and NAHX 54372 was forwarded to a repair facility accordingly.

column168: Sinclair driver V. Christian Kingsford began his trip in Denver, Co at approximately 6am on Sunday September 16th.  He loaded 8200 gallons of gasoline on his tanker truck at the Sinclair terminal in Henderson, CO.  His destination was Grand Junction Colorado with no stops in between.  All information indicated the beginning of this trip was uneventful.      About two and one half hours in to the trip heading westbound down the backside of Vail Pass the driver lost control of his truck.  Information from his onboard XATA computer indicates he may not have had the truck in gear with an average RPM count around 600.  He gradually and steadily began picking up speed until he ran off the right side of the road at 0928 at mile marker 181.  The onboard computer shows his speed at 96 miles per hour at the time of the crash.  The driver made a short call to 911 before the crash stating the truck was out of control.      The tractor came unhitched from the trailer skidding on the passenger side before coming to a stop upright.  The trailer appears to have flipped and/or rolled and came to a stop lying on its right side.      The Vail fire chief reached Bob Akin at the Sinclair trucking terminal in Salt Lake City around 1030.  He made calls to the National Response Center, Colorado Department of Public Health and Environment and began trying to reach someone in the Denver office. The on-duty dispatcher at the Denver office was notified at 1245 of the incident and she called for HAZMAT clean-up and dispatched a truck in an attempt to pump off any remaining gasoline in the tanker.      The impact of the crash ripped two holes in the tanker.  The first hole was in between the second and third compartments about two feet long and one foot wide.  The second hole was on the left side on the top above the second compartment.  It measured approximately four feet long and gaped open about six inches.      5188 gallons of gasoline spilled out on to the ground through these two holes while 3012 gallons was pumped off the truck and recovered.  The estimated time of release was approximately five hours.  The preventative measure taken to mitigate the effect of the release was the dispatch of the closest available tanker to pump off the remaining gasoline.
column169: Sinclair Oil Corporation maintains a good safety record due to our regular safety meetings with drivers and superb maintenance of our equipment.  This accident appears to have occurred due to driver error.  As a result Sinclair will continue to enforce safe driving habits through safety meetings and monitoring of information made available through the use onboard XATA computers.  This includes but is not limited to driver speed reports and daily logs.

column168: Driver was making a delivery of gasoline to a retail location.  Driver had hooked his drop fitting to the UST and next hooked the delivery hose to the drop fitting, but he did not clamp the ears of the delivery hose tight against the drop fitting.  The driver hooked the drop hose to the discharge head on the trailer, when the driver pulled the trailer discharge level and product began to flow the drop hose fell off of the drop fitting attached to the UST.  The driver immediately closed the discharge valve, product flowed for approximately 2-3 seconds.
column169: To prevent recurrences of this issue the driver has been instructed on properly hooking the drop hose to the drop fitting and ensuring the hose clamps are tightly secured before allowing product to flow.

SPILL TECHNICIANS WILLIAM HENDERSON AND RICKEY DAVIS JR DONNED PROPER PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT AND RESPONDED. UPON ARRIVAL, THEY FOUND A  PLASTIC EXPRESS ENVELOPE WITH VISIBLE SIGNS OF LEAKAGE ON THE OUTER PACKAGE. THEY REMOVED THE PACKAGE FROM THE AREA AND BEGAN THEIR INVESTIGATION. UPON THIS INVESTIGATION, THEY FOUND THIS PACKAGE TO CONTAIN A 1 X 26 OZ METAL AEROSOL CAN OF SELIG T-SOLV. DUE TO NO POSITIVE MEANS OF CLOSURE, A TOTAL OF 5 OZ OF THE  PRODUCT WAS LOST. THIS SHIPMENT ARRIVED INTO WILMINGTON VIA TRUCK # 4647.    THIS SHIPMENT WAS NOT DECLARED AS A REGULATED HAZARDOUS MATERIAL.    CLEAR OF SCENE: 1000.    THERE ARE PICTURES ON FILE IN THE HAZMAT OFFICE IN WILMINGTON, OHIO.

column169: No additional comments.

column168: Univar driver was making delivery to his first stop at Valspar in Orangeburg, SC today and as he opened the rear door of the trailer it was smokey inside and was apparent that it was caused from Hydrochloric Acid, he checked and noticed a small leak coming from the front of his trailer. The leak was coming from a drum that had turned over and had a small drip coming from one of the bungs. Our driver contained the spill which was just a drip from the bung in the drum and all totaled a wet spot of about 2 ft. in diameter.  The Valspar dock worker was there also and notified their Safety Director. The Univar driver called in to the Spartanburg branch to report the incident and said that everything was ok but their Safety Director would not let any of his employees assist our driver in getting other products moved to acces the leaking drum. Due to logistics and response time we contacted Nuway Industrial Services to go assist our driver. Within 30 minutes of Nuway's arrival time they had everything cleaned up, all material back on the trailer and our driver continued on to make his deliveries. The bung in the drum that had leaked was checked for proper torque and was delivered to its original destination. Our driver said that he had just taken a break a few miles before arriving at the customer and there was no evidence of a leak at that time and he also went back to see if anything had leaked as he came through the customers parking lot but did not see anything so apparently the drum had just tipped over as he pulled into the customers facility.
column169: Incident was discussed in monthly employee safety meeting and load securement requirements were emphasized, additional load securement training will be included in future monthly meeting.

Driver was exiting the loading terminal, and in an attempt to avoid a construction road crew, he veered too far to the right and made contact with a yellow post with the back of the trailer. The contact caused damage to: two rear loading heads, right spring shackle, hose tray and minor tank damage. The damage led to approximatley 10 gallons of regular unleaded gas to spill. column168: While loading a trailer at the Veolia 10 day intransit facility located in Philadelphia, PA, an employee was placing a cubic yard UN rated fiber box on the end of the trailer. In order to load a cubic yard box, it must be pushed onto the trailer from the back with a forklift vehicle.  While pushing the container onto the trailer, the forklift pierced a drum which caused the leak to the 55 gallon 1A1 DM containing a flammable liquid mixture of methanol and acetonitrile. The forks were slightly longer than the pallet which caused the piercing of the drum behind the cubic yard box. The cleanup was performed by Veolia employees.  Approximately 25 gallons of material was lost from the drum spilling onto the floor of the trailer and onto the sealed pavement of the facility. All cleanup materials (speedi dri, pads) were containerized up for proper disposal and the punctured drum was overpacked into a 85 gallon drum for shipment to the disposal location.
column169: The employee was re-trained on how to properly load containers onto the trailers. The supervisor of the employee also reviewed the proper techniques for paying attention to your surroundings while loading and unloading materials.

On 09/28/07 at 11:18, a Cayuga County 911 Dispatcher notified the CSXT Public Safety Coordination Center that the local fire department was enroute to a stopped train with a report that a railcar was possibly leaking. Upon arrival, fire department personnel found CSX train Q62628 stopped at MP QC 315.37 at the North Main Street Crossing in Port Byron, NY, and tank car UTLX 900176 venting Carbon Dioxide from the protective housing.  CSXT HazMat Manager M.C. Bethge and an emergency response contractor, EP+S of Vermont, responded and discovered the liquid line valve one turn open and the valve plug less than tool tight.  The liquid line valve was closed and the plug was tightened, at which time the release stopped. All valves and fittings inside the protective housing were inspected for closure, the car was re-sealed and tagged and released for disposition.      Chemtrec Report # 20070928-00107.    NARRI: 5(5+1+0)*(3+0)=90  Cause Code=662
column169: As this car was found with it's liquid valve open and plug loose, with the seal intact, it is recommended that the shipper review proper loading practices with loading personnel.

column168: At 1610 hours a yard conductor found HOKX 8342, a loaded tank car of Hydrochloric Acid,  with liquid product on the side of the tank car. The car was isolated, emergency notification procedures implemented, and an emergency response contractor (EP+S of Vermont) dispatched to the scene. Upon investigation, contractor personnel found the gasket between the manway nozzle and the valve body plate to be misaligned, with approximately 1 quart of product splashed around the manway area of the tank car.  Contractor personnel re-inserted the gasket and tightened the bolts and neutralized the Hydrochloric Acid on the top and side of the tank car.  The shipper, PCI Chemicals Canada Company was notified of the repair, and the car was forwarded for disposition.      Chemtrec report 20070924-00157      NARRI: 2(5+5+0)*(2+0)=40  Cause Code=220
column169: The shipper is encouraged to review their pre-trip inspection and loading procedures.

column168: On September 26, 2007 at 21:20 hours, personnel reported seeing vapors coming from the top of HOKX 8342 when coupling at the CSXT Niagara Yard in Niagara Falls, NY. The car was isolated, emergency notification procedures initiated and the Occidental Chemical response team responded. Responders found vapors were coming from the manway nozzle gasket which had cracked. Occidental personnel wrapped the manway nozzle and valve plate with plastic to mitigate the vapor release, and the tank car was moved to an isolation track for further repairs. On September 28, 2007, Occidental personnel made repairs to the manway nozzle gasket with epoxy putty, reset the manway valve plate and tested the tank car for securement. The car was delivered to the facility on October 20 for unloading.      Chemtrec Report #20070927-00140   Cause Code: 221  NARRI:  2(5+5+0) x (2+0) = 40
column169: The shipper is encouraged to review proper gasket securement for this commodity.

column168: Florida Rock & Tank Lines, Inc Driver was delivering regular unleaded to a customer location. The driver mis-read the tank chart and attempted to load 6500 gallons into a tank that at the time would only hold 5500. The driver prepared to unload and chose to use his coax fitting but did not hook his vapor line up. As a result when the fuel was overfilled it began to leak out of the vapor hole. Driver immediately shut off flow of product but approximately 5 gallons had leaked. All product was contained on concrete, no product went into drain or soil. Cleaned up by in-house personnel.
column169: Driver must take time to perform procedures properly and according to standards.

column168: GATX 47190 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) was reported leaking product from the top valve area during normal switching of a BNSF inbound train that arrived earlier in the railyard. GATX 47190 was carefully moved and isolated in the railyard awaiting further inspection. BNSF and shipper contract responders reported finding the liquid valve open with its non-metal closure plug cross-threaded with damaged/cracked threads. The valve was closed and the closure plug was replaced in kind. Contract responders neutralized and cleaned the spillage residue on the tank shell of GATX 47190 by 1430 hrs. PDT, 9/30/07. No product spillage impacted the ground.

The leak was discovered during a vehicle inspection. An internal emergency response was initiated and it was eventually determined that a single container, out of a load of 28, had begun to leak from what appeared to be pin-holes "likely" caused by corrosion from within the container. It was estimated that roughly 200 millileters of liqui had spilled onto the asphalt surface of the temporary storage lot.      The leaker(s) were identified as 55 gallon 1A1 closed-head drums containing waste perchloroethylene solution. Upon inspection, the container was found to have one or more pin-holes on the outer surface.     The offending container was overpacked for shipment.
column169: The offeror was notified of the leak. At the time of the leak it was determined that the container type was appropriate for the material being shipped. Events of a few days later would prove otherwise. That is, the perchloroethylene has apparently begun to go "acidic."

column168: Vehicle carrying hazardous material was at a full stop in heavy congestion as construction was being performed on Hwy 99. Stopped behind our vehicle was a mini-van. A tractor trailer travelling behind the mini-van failed to seetraffic was stopped and struck the mini-van; pushing it out of the lane of traffic. The tractor-trailer continued forward striking our hazmat vehicle sending it off the road and down an embankment. The force of the impact was severe enough to break parts-bins and shelves from their mounts, and break containers free of their cargo straps, causing containers to careen through the van; some puncturing.     After coming to rest, our driver retrieved his 'driver's book' containing his daily load sheet (which was kept by theresponding CHP officer) and MSDS for each product on his truck.    Damage to the cargo-box door rendered it inoperable until emergency responders were on-scene. Thosecontainers that were punctured or damaged continued to leak until that time; some 30 minutes. Hazmat clean-upcontractors isolated the spill and, erring on the side of safety, removed all contents of our truck treating all contents contaminated by class 8 corrosives.
column169: It is unlikely that any additional measures could be taken to protect against such a catastrophic event. Better enforcement of highway regulations; especially focusing on speeding and commercial vehicles that follow tooclosely might gradually improve highway safety.

Soon thereafter, the jurisdictional federal agency (i.e. USCG), local police and fire departments, as well as the port authority and an environmental response contractor, were contacted in order to initiate remediation of the incident. The leaking substance was identified as one of the hazardous commodities contained therein (i.e. UN 2789, ACETIC ACID, GLACIAL in plastic drums). The cause of the spill was determined to be due to the overturning of an improperly secured drum, thus allowing the commodity to leak through a package vent closure. All spilled material was recovered and properly salvage packed for subsequent transportation and disposal by the environmental contractor. END OF REPORT

column169: On The Kansas City Southern Railway (KCSR), shippers are immediately notified of all HAZMAT releases.  For non-accident releases (a.k.a. package or closure defects), where possible, shippers (responsible party) are requested to respond, repair and remediate.  By immediately involving the shipper, in-depth knowledge of the release cause is gained by the same organization that can implement process changes to prevent recurrence.  After each NAR incident, KCSR provides outreach to the shipper to help investigate root-cause factors for correction.  For non-accident related releases, the shipper should be contacted directly for details associated with actions taken to prevent recurrence.

column168: Car inspector while walking track observed car ADMX 30607 leaking from top of car. Car Inspector contacted Trainmaster who is Hazmat qualified through Incident Command level and Manager of Hazardous Materials. Subsequent investigation revealed that car was leaking under valve dome. Upon removing seal it was observed that leak was emanating from liquid valve stem. Pressure was relieved off the car by actuating the vacuum relief device and slightly opening the vapor valve which stopped leak.  Upon stopping leak, packing nut which was deep seated on liquid valve was removed to check packing material condition. Packing material was observed to be non existent either due to age and/or other reasons. Packing material was applied to valve stem, along with packing nut and car was repaired to good order after checking for any further leaks. With no leaks noted car was released for delivery with shipper and consignee advised of the incident.  Note: Product that leaked almost instantaneously evaporated due to 90 F temperature and  WSW winds of 17 mph. There was no environmental impact noted in the area of the leak  Additionally no injuries and/or reports of inhalation were noted.
column169: Preparer of this report requested of car owner, ADM to inspect car upon off loading and to inspect liquid valve for deterioration of packing material as well as valve assembly. ADM advised that car would be removed from fleet service for inspection and repaired if warranted. ADM further requested to investigate why packing nut was so deep seated.

column168: Most of this Hydrochloric acid delivery proceeded as normal. The product was being unloaded though a valve at the top of the cargo tank. The cargo tank was a little over half-full at the start of unloading with approximately 3,000 gallons aboard, so internal air pressure developed gradually. The tractor air compressor was used since plant compressed air was not readily available. A maximum of about 10 p.s.i. of air pressure was used to begin the product moving from the tank trailer to the plant line which runs up the side of the building and into a plant acid storage tank.  About 30 minutes into a typical 40 minute delivery, the driver and another person in the area noted that product began spraying from the rear underside of the trailer. The driver immediately shut off the air line valve and replaced his half-face respirator with his full-face respirator. He identified the leaking of a capped-off and safety-wired valve at the base of the trailer tank. A small hole had developed in the exterior steel valve wall of the rubber-lined valve, which was now spraying acid out onto the trailer undercarriage, where it flowed and pooled on the plant loading dock ramp area. The driver described it as looking similar to a home water pipe that develops a small crack from freezing, spraying its contents out (but this cause was apparently lining failure and internal corrosion of steel by acid instead of the mechanical effects of freezing water). There were other drivers and employees in the general area, so word of the incident traveled quickly to plant management.  A plant spill response team rallied, and they were soon joined by various emergency responders and governmental agency representatives. This Safety Director notified the National Spill Response Center and directed the driver to call 9-1-1 as they advised. This was followed by discussion of the events with representatives of the Federal EPA, the State of Ohio EPA, Great West Casualty Company (this carrier’s insurance company), and later to the Cleveland Division of the Environment.  With the permission of the Incident Commander, the driver lowered the trailer dolly legs, released the fifth-wheel’s kingpin latch and pulled the tractor out from under the trailer. Then he was able to lower the front (uphill) end of the trailer to keep some of the remaining product contained in the trailer tank, as the product ran forward, away from the leaking valve. Note that the bottom valve wall developed the hole. The defective valve  was “closed” the entire time. The valve wall leaked, but there was no leaking from the capped bottom valve opening. Closing the top unloading valve had no effect on the leak.  The shipper was able to arrange for a truck from their Mini-Bulk fleet to arrive on scene equipped with an acid-resistant diaphragm pump. The leaking became less forceful as the trailer tank pressure bled off, so emergency responders were able to use containment devices to collect much of the leaking liquid once

column168: According to the information obtained, the following occurred.  While in the process of offloading freight, there was a release to a shipment of 1 of 3 fiberboard boxes, at 1 liter each, containing UN1987 Alcohols, n.o.s.  Apparently, 1 fiberboard box was damaged and released approximately 1 liter of product due to improper handling.  The free product was contained to the tar mack at the BAX Global, Inc. facility.  BAX Global, Inc. performed clean up using gloves and ½ a 40 pound bag of floor dry.  Approximately 20 pounds of waste were generated and placed into one (1) 30-gallon steel recovery drum.  BAX Global, Inc. will coordinate disposal internally, in accordance with local, state, and federal regulations.  The remainder of the shipment was forwarded to the consignee.  The MSDS was requested and received.  No injuries or exposures were reported.
column169: Since the release was accidental, and appears to be related to mishandling, no plans currently exist to prevent recurrence.  BAX Global Inc. will continue to reinforce safe handling procedures and guidelines to all personnel.

column168: On September 25, 2007 at approximately 1300 facility personnel at Clean Harbors Environmental Services’ 10-day in-transit storage facility located in Chicago, IL identified a minor release of a hazardous waste from a non-bulk package loaded onto a van trailer.  The facility manager was immediately notified and an in-house response crew was dispatched to identify the source of release and to initiate all necessary corrective actions.  Upon review of the paperwork, the emergency response crew donned appropriate protective equipment and entered the trailer.  Once inside trailer, the response crew determined that the cause of the release was attributed to a 55-gallon non-bulk package that had tipped over in-transit allowing approximately 20 gallons of a corrosive material to escape from the top closure of the package.  Please note that approximately 5 gallons did escape from the trailer onto a fully contained concrete parking area below.  The container was placed in the upright position and the crew applied chemically compatible absorbent to absorb and contain the released material.  The package involved in this incident was placed into a suitable salvage drum and all of the absorbent material was collected and placed into appropriate container for disposal at fully licensed hazardous waste management facility.
column169: Our investigation determined that the cause of the incident was improper preparation for transportation and inadequate cargo blocking and bracing.  The driver as well as the individuals involved in the execution of this particular operation have been re-instructed in the selection of proper containers and proper blocking and bracing techniques.

According to the information obtained, the following occurred.  While offloading freight at customer location, a pallet was discovered crushed inside the trailer.  Two (2) cartons were damaged, which resulted in the release of approximately 8 gallons of free product.  The Meadowbrook Fire Department was contacted to assess the site.  Upon arrival, the Meadowbrook FD applied absorbent material to the free product, and containerized the damaged freight.  H.M.H.T.T.C., Inc. of Wilmington, Delaware was dispatched to perform the remainder of cleanup.  Upon inspection of the trailer, H.M.H.T.T.C., Inc. discovered that the free product had contaminated the surrounding cartons around the pallet.  H.M.H.T.T.C., Inc. proceeded to containerize the contaminated freight.  All in tact freight was repalletized and reshrinwrapped, to be sent on to its destination.  Three (3) 55-gallon drums, which contained the spent absorbent material, contaminated cartons, and damaged freight, were generated during the cleanup.  Disposal was coordinated by H.M.H.T.T.C., Inc. in accordance with local, state, and federal regulations.  There were no injuries or exposures reported.
column169: Since the release was accidental, appears to be related to the shipment being crushed in transit, no plans currently exist to prevent recurrence.  Cardinal Health will continue to reinforce safe handling procedures and driver safety to all personnel.

The valve was warmed to ambient temperature and tightened which stopped the leak.

column25: Hyundai Intermodal Inc. for Formosa Plastics Corp.
column62: Impact with Sharp or Protruding Object (e.g., nails)
column168: Intermodal facility workers reported an unknown substance leaking from under the container doors of HDMU 213210 which was parked in the intermodal parking lot. HDMU 213210 was carefully moved to the containment area for further observation and investigation. Consignee contract responders reported finding 50 pound paper bags of product stacked on pallets. Seven of these bags were found leaking product from nail puncture holes incurred by nail protrusions from the wooden blocking and bracing (B+B) used to secure the lading inside this container. The leaking dry product mixed with moisture/water and this slurry type mixture was observed leaking from HDMU 213210. The damaged bags were placed into two 55 gallon poly lined salvage drums. All spillage was neutralized and cleaned. The protruding nails were hammered back into the wooden B+B to ensure a smooth surface. All non-compromised lading was returned inside the cleaned HDMU 213210 container properly blocked and braced. The salvage drums were removed by the contractor and taken to their facility for appropriate future disposal.    The origin of this shipment was from Formosa Plastics Corporation in Taipei, Taiwan and received in the U.S. at the Port of Long Beach, CA. The named consignee was Connell Brothers Company Ltd. of San Francisco, CA. and destined for a warehouse in Houston, TX.

While loading a trailer at Veolia's 10-day intransit facility located in Philadelphia, PA, a drum was accidentally punctured by the forks of a forklift vehicle.  A trained Veolia supervisor was attempting to load a cubic yard box onto the end of the trailer,(which involves pushing the cubic yard box onto the trailer from the dock), when he accidently punctured a drum with the fork. This was caused by the fork protruding approximately 203 inches beyond the edge of the pallet of the cubic yard box.  The drum was punctured and the material puddled onto the sealed asphalt pavement. The material was cleaned up using speedi dry and absorbant pads. The punctured drum was overpacked into an 85 gallon container, and all spill material cleaned up by onsite personal. The spill material never left the sealed portion of the asphalt.
column169: The employee's supervisor had a short training discussion with the employee on proper loading techniques. The forklift that was being used was a rental lift that was being utilized while the regular forklift was in for maintenance. The forks on the rental lift were slightly longer than the forks on our lift. Since then, our lift has returned from service and all facility employees have been retrained on the forklift on the dock. A signed copy of the training sheet was placed into the training sign-in folder.

column168: Driver dropped one of his three tanker compartments of Ultra Low Sulfur Diesel into the customer’s underground storage tank. After the delivery of the first compartment, driver removed his delivery hose from the customer’s storage tank to verify adequate storage. Driver failed to reconnect the deilvery hose after verifying that the tank had adequate storage. Driver then opened the discharge valve on his second compartment spilling 40 gallons of Ultra Low Sulfur Diesel onto the pavement The spilled diesel covered an area of approximatly 1,000 square feet. The driver, Deltona Fire Dept. and the customer’s employees contained the spill with booms & oil dry until Mckenzie Tank Lines emergency responders arrived on scene to clean up the spill.    Note — Initial assessment by Deltona Fire Dept. states the spill was caused by overtilling the storage tank. After further investigation, Deltona Fire Dept concluded that the spill was caused by the driver’s failure to reconnect his hose after verifying adequate tank storage.

column62: Corrosion - Exterior; Loose Closure, Component, or Device
column168: On 9/26/07 at 0930 our terminal manager began unloading ferric chloride solution from a rail car to a truck. We use air pressure to off load the rail cars and use a bolted flange connection that is attached from the top of the railcar. This is then connected to a quick connect fitting above the valve and a hose goes over to the truck that is to be loaded.   About 20 minutes into the loading process one of the four bolts on the flange failed   allowing product to spray from the railcar between our flange fitting and the railcar   fitting. Our manager immediately took the air pressure of the car and then tried to tighten the bolt back down but was unable to stop the leak. The car continued for 10 minutes to release product as the pressure came off the car. After failing to be able to tighten the bolt the manager climbed down off the railcar and with the help of two other terminal employees they used our spill containment kit to contain the spill. Our facility is   completely self-contained so product is unable to be release off the property. Our   employees contained the spill to a small area 3 feet by 20 feet and used soda ash on site to neutralize the spill and soak up the ferric chloride solution. They then swept up the soda ash and place in 55 gallon drums.
column169: It was discovered that the bolt that failed was pitted from corrosion and should have been replaced when the flange was put on. We have also changed our SOP to include bolt inspection and that only stainless steel or Teflon coated bolts could be used in attaching the flange. We immediately order all new stainless steel bolts for the Baltimore terminal.

column168: PLAINS TRUCK DRIVER ROGER B. SIMMONS WAS TRAVELING SOUTH ON COUNTY ROAD 51 WHEN HE ATTEMPTED TO MOVE TO HIS RIGHT TO ALLOW EXTRA ROOM WHEN MEETING AN ONCOMING TRUCK; SLID OVER THE EDGE OF THE ASPHALT OFF THE ROADWAY, AND ROLLED THE TRUCK AND TRAILER COMBINATION 90 DEGREE INTO THE NORTH BARROW DITCH. THE ROLLOVER ENDED WITH THE TRUCK/TRAILER COMING TO REST ON THE PASSENGER SIDE. AT THE TIME OF DISCOVERY BY PLAINS AND THE NEW MEXICO STATE POLICE, THE DRIVER HAD FREED HIMSELF FROM THE TRUCK AND SUFFERED NO INJURIES. THE CARGO TANK RUPTURE ALLOWED 2 BARRELS OF CRUDE OIL TO LEAK ONTO THE BARROW DITCH AREA OF THE ROADWAY. THE TRUCK DRIVER AND PLAINS' SPILL REPSONSE TEAM CONTAINED THE SPILL USING CONTAINMENT BOOMS, ABSORBMENTS AND SOIL BERMS. DURATION OF THE SPILL WAS APPROXIMATELY 1/2 HOUR. THE CARGO TANK RUPTURE WAS A CIRCUMFERENTIAL BREAK IN THE BOTTOM OF THE TANK SHELL, APPROXIMATELY 9' BEHIND THE FRONT BULKHEAD, APPROXIMATELY 3.50" IN LENGTH, AND 0.0187" IN WIDTH AT ITS WIDEST POINT. THE CARGO TANK GOUGE/BREAK OCCURRED WHEN THE TANK BOTTOM CONTACTED THE REAR TRUCK FRAME RAIL DURING THE ROLLOVER.  PLEASE SEE ATTACHED DIAGRAM AND PHOTOGRAPHS FOR ADDITIONAL REFERENCE AND DESCRIPTION.
column169: 1. PHOTOGRAPHS AND DETAILS OF INCIDENT USED IN SAFETY MEETINGS AND DRIVER SAFETY TRAINING PRESENTATIONS TO IMPROVE AND HEIGHTEN DRIVER AWARENESS AND ATTENTION.  2. column168: OHFL driver Robert was in route from Corning, Ca on I-5 when he heard a loud bang from the inside of his trailer. Robert proceeded to exit his vehicle and began walking towards the rear of his trailer to examine where the sound came from. column168: The drums had been removed from a 20' container in order to block and brace to AAR standards. A forklift operator was setting a pallet behind the drums and the forks were protruding in front of the pallet. The forks struck the drumand ripped a hole in the side of it as the he lowered the forks. The duration of the release was about 5 minutes. column168: DURING DELIVERY THE EARS ON HOSE CAME OFF RESULTING IN A SPILL OF APPROXIMATELY 120 GALLONS OF DIESEL. A REMEDIATION COMPANY WAS CALLED TO THE SCENE TO CONDUCT A CLEAN UP.

The package was dropped in handling.  Examination of the inner container revealed a ruptured seam which allowed the contents to escape. The leakage was contained.  The undamaged portion of the package was repacked for return to shipper.

THE DRIVER ARRIVED AT THE CONSIGNER SITE AT 2100 HRS ON 20 SEPT 07. HE BEGAN UNLOADING USING COMPRESSED AIR (ABOUT 25PSI). THE UNLOADING PROCESS VIA THIS METHOD WOULD NORMALLY TAKE LESS THAN 2 HOURS TO COMPLETE. HOWEVER, AFTER OVER TWO HOURS VERY LITTLE PRODUCT WAS TRANSFERED TO THE CUSTOMER'S HOLDING TANK. AT OBOO ON 21 SEPT 07 HE ACQUIRED PERMISSION TO USE A PUMP TO TRANSFER PRODUCT AND ENGAGED THE PUMP WITHIN ONE MINUTE THE HOSE RUPTURED SPRAYING APPROXIMATELY 50 GALLONS OF PRODUCT. SOME PRODUCT SPRAYED ONTO THE TRACTOR AND TRAILER. AFTER AN ONSIGHT INVESTIGATION COONSIGNEE EMPLOYEES DISCOVERED THAT THEIR PRODUCT LINES WERE CLOGGED WITH SOLIDS WHICH PREVENTED OFF LOADING VIA COMPRESSED AIR TO FURTHER COMPLICATE MATTERS THE PUMPS BYPASS WAS INCORRECTLY INSTALLED AND DID NOT ENGAGE AT REACHING 35-50PSI AND WELL OVER EXCEEDED THE HOSES DESIGN PRESSURE RATING OF 200 PSI AND CAUSING IT TO BURST.
column169: ALL PUMPS/BYPASSES SHOULD BE  REQUIRED TO BE TESTED/CERTIFIED AFTER INSTALLATION, REPAIR, AND ON AN ANNUAL BASIS. THERE IS NOTHING REGULATORY REQUIRING THIS. EVEN THE MANUFACTURER (ROPPER) HAS WRITTEN LITTLE/NO SUGGESTED MAINTENANCE/INSPECTION/TESTING. SINCE THIS INCIDENT WE HAVE SET A POLICY IN AFFECT TO INSPECT AND TEST PUMPS ON AN ANNUAL SCHEDULE AND FOLLOWING INSTALLATION AND MAINTENANCE.

column58: Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Reclosing
column168: While loading our MC331 trailer, the pressure built up to a point and the pressure relief valve started venting on top of the tank.  The trailer was 60% full at the time of the release.  It reset but continued to seep so the product was unloaded off of the trailer.      The tank was taken to Woodys Fabrication in Corpus Christi, TX where both the front and rear relief valves were replaced.  There was nothing visibly wrong with the failed valve and the shop failed to bench test it.      The shipper in this case was not able to connect a vapor return line from the loading rack to their system so it appears they over pressuried our tank.
column169: I suggested that the shipper supply a vapor return line from their system to the loading rack so the pressure could equalize during the loading process.

column168: Tank Car ECLX 30076 was found leaking from the top of the car. A UP employee reported seeing a vapor cloud at the top of the car, and evidence that some liquid product had been released. No injuries were reported, and no drains or waterways were impacted. Local authorities were notified. At approximately 11:11 Hrs, Oskaloosa Dispatch informed UP that a “precautionary” evacuation was ordered  the Incident Commander (IC). At approximately 12:45 hrs, Mark Maday, Manager Hazardous Materials Management, arrived on scene and received a briefing from the Incident Commander. Mr. Maday advised the IC that the evacuation could be lifted since the commodity presented no risk to the general public. The IC informed Mr. Maday that he wanted the car evaluated first and would then decide if the evacuation should be lifted. At approximately 13:40 hrs, Mr. Maday reported that he had completed the inspection of the car, and that the cause of the leak was the Safety Vent Assembly. He stated that a nut had come off of one of the bolts that secures the Safety Vent Assembly to the car. He further advised that the loss of the nut allowed the Vent Assembly to lean and provide a pathway for product out of the car. Maday stated that the missing nut was still on the car and in good condition. However, a new nut was purchased locally, and he completed the repair to the car so that it could be moved. Mr. Maday also stated that the IC gave the order to lift the evacuation at approximately 13:29 Hrs. At approximately 14:21 Hrs, Mr. Maday reported that the car had been resecured and that the car was being moved off of the crossing and into the yard, and that normal operations were getting underway. Mr. Maday stated that he has talked with the shipper, ERCO Worldwide, and that a contact team was enroute to re-Inspect the car before it moved to destination. At approximately 08:00 hrs on September 25, Mr. Maday reported that he has talked with Mr. Randy Rowe, ERCO Worldwide, and that the Safety Vent Assembly had been reinspected and checked for tightness, and that a complete re-inspection of the car had been completed and that the load could be moved to destination.

column168: On 9/10/2007 at 1818, HMHTTC was notified by CRST International of a suspected varnish spill leaking from the back of a trailer in Belmont County OH. Upon response teams arrival, a pallet of cans containing varnish were found to have been crushed by the weight of pallets and material placed on top of it. The area impacted by the spilled product was limited to the area directly surrounding the pallet inside the trailer and directly below the trailer on the ground outside. It was estimated that less than 1 gallon of material was outside of the trailer on the ground.Pallets of small boxes that were on top of the pallet of varnish were broken down and removed. After the stacked pallets were removed, it was found that there were twenty-four (24) 1 gallon cans on the pallet, of which twelve (12) were damaged, spilling a total of approximately 2 gallons. The damaged containers were removed and packaged intoa 17H 55g drum along with all cleanup debris. The removed pallets were then re-stacked and wrapped in plastic.The drum of damaged cans and debris were properly disposed of in accordance with all state and federal regulations.

column168: ICTF Security reported a leaking container in the ICTF Railyard, Long Beach, CA. The container, PGRU 230657, was parked at Green Space 462. Dean Cooper, Manager, Hazardous Materials was notified and stated Transloading Environmental would be sent out to inspect and conduct remediation as required. At 06:O6AM, Manager Cooper stated Transloading Environmental, contractor, was on scene and would have to unload the container to identify where the leak was originating. Mr. Cooper further stated approximately five gallons had leaked onto the ground, and had been contained with absorbent. 14e requested shipper notification through Chemtrec, and the Los Angeles City Fire Department be notified for information only. He further stated it would be three to four hours before they would be able to determine where the leak originated as the entire lading was 55 gallon drums. During the off loading, it was noted a one inch honeycombed cardboard had been used for the bi-level separation. Almost every drum in the top tier had spun and ‘cookie’ cut through the cardboard, to the point where six drums on the floor had been deheaded by the top drums spinning. A total of 32 drums were damaged and leaking, estimating approximately 700 gallons of product had been lost during transit. The remaining 40 drums were so severely damaged that they were deemed unfit for further transportation. All of the leaking drums were patched and placed into salvage drums for containment. The remaining drums were placed back into the original container for temporary storage. Shipper contact developed the best course was to properly dispose of the lading. Arrangements were made to dispose of the entire lading.

column168: At 07:38 AM on 9-6-08, Frank Lerch, Manager Hazardous Materials was contacted by the RMCC, and advised that Gilbert Coronado, Car Foreman, reported a strong odor coming from an unknown tank car. The tankcar was on storage track 6, in the Strang Yard at Mile Post 21.36 of the Strang Subdivision In La Porte, TX.  Mgr. Lerch responded, and identified loaded tank car CALX 3033 to be leaking  product from the bottom outlet valve. Mgr. Lerch placed a bucket under the car to contain the leak. Product was dripping from the valve at a rate of approximately 1 drop every 15 seconds with no pooling of product. Inspection of the car revealed the top operated bottom outlet valve to be open two turns, the packing gland nut loose three turns, and the bottom outlet valve cap was hanging from the safety chain, not attached to the bottom outlet valve nozzle. Additionally, the A end placard was illegible and the B end placard was missing. Mr. Lerch correct all noted exceptions and released the car to continue onto destination without further incident. There was no remediation required as product evaporated upon contacted with the atmosphere. At 09:17 AM, Mgr. Lerch spoke to shipper representative Steve Givens, Product Stewardship, Mgr. Transportation Compliance for Cook Composites. Mgr. Lerch advised Mr. Givens of noted exceptions, and corrective actions taken.  There were no reported injuries, drains, or waterways impacted resulting  from this release.
