column168: At 08:55 AM on 9-17-07, Frank Lerch, Manager Hazardous Materials was contacted by the RMCC, and advised that Drew Duncan, Car Foreman, reported yard personnel had observed tank car TILX 190039 leak an unknown amount of product. The tankcar was located on the north end of Track 307 at the Settegast Yard in Houston, TX. Mgr. Lerch responded and advised the RMCC to make shipper notification via Chem-Trec.  On arrival Mgr. Lerch noted that the car was not leaking, and determined that the car released product from the manway opening only when it was moved. Inspection of the car revealed the manway gasket to be in very poor condition, additionally six of six manway swing bolts were in proper position, not wrench tight. Mgr. Lerch replaced the worn manway gasket with  a Gortex Gasket, and tightened the six manway swing bolts, which made the car safe for transportation. There was no additional remediation necessary as leaked product had evaporated upon contact with the atmosphere.  Upon proper securement of the car, it  was released to continue onto destination without further incident. At approximately 09:30 AM, Mgr. Lerch spoke to shipper representative Milton Beliard, Business Developer for L& M Traffic and advised him of the noted exceptions to the car, and corrective actions taken.  There were no drains or waterways impacted, or reported injuries resulting from this release.  Manway original seal JJ  Keller # 1102177, replaced with UPRR CTS 0008749.

column168: Rudolph Hill, Manager of Yard Operations, reported loaded Tankcar GATX 7484 was releasing an unknown amount of product from the top of the tankcar on the south end of Track 443 in the Beaumont Railyard near Mile Post 25 of the Sabine Industrial Lead inBeaumont, TX. Tim O'Brien, Regional Manager of Hazardous Material, was notified and responded. Mr.O'Brien found the release was caused by a misaligned gasket and a stripped bolt on the quick fill hole. Mr O'Brien re-aligned the gasket and Rescar replaced the defective swing bolt. The car was decontaminated and released.

column168: THE MATERIALS WERE IN HIGHWAY TRANSIT WHEN THE TRACTOR-TRAILER WAS INVOLVED IN A MULTI-VEHICLE COLLISION.  AS A RESULT OF THE ACCIDENT, THE TRACTOR-TRAILER BURNED.  FUEL AND ENGINE FLUIDS WERE RELEASED AS WELL AS AN UNDERMINDED QUANTITY OF THE CLEANERS (FLAMMABLE AND CAUSTIC LIQUIDS).  A PORTION OF THE MATERIALS WERE CONSUMED IN THE FIRE.  LOCAL FIRE AND LAW ENFORCEMENT RESPONDED, AND A PRIVATE HAZMAT RESPONSE COMPANY WAS RETAINED.  THE UNDAMAGED CARGO WAS RECOVERED AND PALLETIZED.  IMPACTED SOILS WERE EXCAVATED, AND DEBRIS WAS RECOVERED AND STAGED IN ROLL OFF BOXES FOR DISPOSAL.  IMPACTED WATER FROM THE FIRE FIGHTING OPERATIONS WAS ALSO RECOVERED FOR DISPOSAL.

column168: THE HENIFF TRANSPORTATION TRACTOR TRAILER UNIT WAS CROSSING A SET OF RAILROAD TRACKS WHEN IT WAS HIT IN THE REAR BY ANOTHER TRACTOR TRAILER OPERATED BY FALCON TRANSPORT.  THE FALCON TRUCK HIT THE HENIFF TRUCK AT A SPEED IN EXCESS OF 60MPH.  UPON IMPACT THE TWO AXLES ON THE HENIFF TRAILER WERE KNOCKED OFF THE FRAME AND THE IMPACT CAUSED A LEAK IN THE TRAILER.  THE FUEL TANK ON THE RIGHT SIDE OF THE FALCON TRACTOR WAS KNOCKED COMPLETELY OFF THE TRACTOR AND THE DRIVERS SIDE FUEL TANK WAS LEAKING ALSO.  EMERGENCY RESPONDERS WERE ON THE SCENE AND A HAZMAT CLEANUP TEAM WAS CALLED IN TO CLEAN UP THE LEAKING MATERIAL AND DIESEL FUEL WITH THE INVOLVEMENT OF THE INDIANA DOT AND INDIANA EMA.  ADDITIONAL REMEDIATION TOOK PLACE UNDER THE INDIANA EPA'S SUPERVISION.
column169: THE FACT THAT HAZMAT LOADS ARE REQUIRED TO COME TO A COMPETE STOP AT ALL RAILROAD GRADE CROSSINGS BEFORE PROCEEDING COULD BE CONSIDERED A FACTOR.  THIS WAS A TWO LANE ROAD AND THE FALCON TRANSIT DRIVER MAY NOT HAVE BEEN AWARE THAT THE HENIFF VEHICLE WAS CROSSING THE TRACKS AT SUCH A SLOW RATE OF SPEED AFTER STOPPING AND CHECKING PRIOR TO CROSSING THE TRACKS.

column168: FILE- 07-103 DOT & OMC SHIPPER- INDIVIDUAL NOT A COMPANY AWB#- TMB 2331 7353754 PWT  ON 09/07/2007 AT 1129, AN ODOROUS SHIPMENT WAS REPORTED IN “D” BUILDING LOCATED AT THE DHL MAIN SORT FACILITY, 145 HUNTER DRIVE, WILMINGTON, OHIO 451 77. SPILL TECHNICIANS CECEILA HICKEY AND MATTHEW PHILLIPS DONNED PROPER PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT AND RESPONDED. UPON ARRIVAL, THEY FOUND A FIBERBOARD BOX WITH VISIBLE SIGNS OF LEAKAGE ON THE OUTER PACKAGE AND EMITTING A GASOLINE ODOR. THEY REMOVED THE  PACKAGE FROM THE AREA AND BEGAN THEIR INVESTIGATION. UPON THIS INVESTIGATION, THEY FOUND THIS PACKAGE TO CONTAIN A WATER PUMP WITH GASOLINE INSIDE OF THE TANK. DUE TO A LOOSE CLOSURE ON THE TANK, A TOTAL OF 1 OZ OF THE PRODUCT WAS LOST. THIS SHIPMENT ARRIVED INTO WILMINGTON VIA TRUCK # 5250.  THIS SHIPMENT WAS NOT DECLARED AS A REGULATED HAZARDOUS MATERIAL.  CLEAR OF SCENE: 1214.  THERE ARE PICTURES ON FILE IN THE HAZMAT OFFICE IN WILMINGTON, OHIO.

Passenger attempted to board Midwest Airlines flight 508 from Kansas City (MCI) to Fort Myers (RSW) with a Helios 300 portable oxygen device (see attached photo). Flight crew observed device and advised station personnel of its existence. Passenger was rerouted on another airline to continue her journey.  Subsequent investigation revealed the passenger had arrived at Kansas City from Milwaukee (MKE) on Midwest Airlines flight 918 earlier that day. It was also determined the passenger presented the device to the airline ground staff in MKE but was not prevented from traveling with the device, and the passenger was also allowed by flight attendants to use the device during the MKE-MCI flight. Midwest Airlines status as a “will-not carry” airline does not authorize the transportation of devices containing Oxygen, refrigerated liquid.
column169: Passenger acceptance personnel will be retrained to emphasize devices allowed and not allowed on company flights, including examples with photographs to help eliminate any confusion.
